D\":\"agent_msg_01HJNoqk1URu2wWHAzC59tam\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01TAAHUAkVJTks2M5qBDK6BD\",\"uuid\":\"4a1285e4-0400-47f4-977b-f6dd69f3a374\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-01T20:13:37.758Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"4a1285e4-0400-47f4-977b-f6dd69f3a374\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"db57b693-b4f5-47da-9cc5-651e9169ac1d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"skip-fully-condensed-sessions\",\"slug\":\"cozy-napping-bachman\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Agent\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01QCFR9pgvxo8KHSPiXfzXDC\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01QCFR9pgvxo8KHSPiXfzXDC\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-01T20:13:36.965Z\",\"uuid\":\"5f824b4e-0e95-4167-8650-381586a625ce\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"ecb265c1-cc8a-470e-8d85-8536ed4c269c\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"db57b693-b4f5-47da-9cc5-651e9169ac1d\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"skip-fully-condensed-sessions\",\"slug\":\"cozy-napping-bachman\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01QCFR9pgvxo8KHSPiXfzXDC\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have a thorough understanding of the full context. Let me provide the review.\\n\\n---\\n\\nHere is my analysis of the five specific questions, followed by additional findings.\\n\\n## 1. Is the skip check in the right place (before expensive operations)?\\n\\n**Yes, the placement is optimal.** The skip at line 783 in `PostCommit` is before `postCommitProcessSession`, which does the expensive work: shadow branch resolution (`repo.Reference` + `CommitObject` + `Tree`), content detection (`sessionHasNewContent`), state machine transition, and condensation. All of that is correctly bypassed.\\n\\nHowever, there is a subtle observation: the skip check currently only guards the **trailer-present path** in `PostCommit`. Fully-condensed ENDED sessions are also iterated in two other call sites that could benefit from the same optimization:\\n\\n- **`filterSessionsWithNewContent`** (line 1104) -- called from `PrepareCommitMsg` at line 355. This iterates all sessions and calls `sessionHasNewContent` for each. A fully-condensed ENDED session will resolve shadow branches and check transcripts unnecessarily. It will return false because there is no new content, but the work is wasted. Since `PrepareCommitMsg` runs synchronously in the git hook path (blocking `git commit`), this is user-facing latency.\\n\\n- **`postCommitUpdateBaseCommitOnly`** (line 1059) -- called when there is no trailer. This already filters to `state.Phase.IsActive()` at line 1075, so fully-condensed ENDED sessions are naturally skipped. No issue here.\\n\\n**Recommendation**: Add the `FullyCondensed` skip to `filterSessionsWithNewContent`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) filterSessionsWithNewContent(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository, sessions []*SessionState) []*SessionState {\\n    var result []*SessionState\\n    for _, state := range sessions {\\n        if state.FullyCondensed {\\n            continue\\n        }\\n        // ...existing logic...\\n    }\\n    return result\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis saves a `sessionHasNewContent` call per fully-condensed session on every `git commit` invocation, not just those with trailers.\\n\\n## 2. Could the `sessions` slice itself be filtered earlier?\\n\\n**Yes, but the trade-off is marginal.** `findSessionsForWorktree` (line 105 in `manual_commit_session.go`) could filter out fully-condensed sessions. However, this would prevent `handleAmendCommitMsg` (line 516) from finding the `LastCheckpointID` on fully-condensed sessions -- which is their entire reason for persisting. The amend path iterates `sessions` looking for `state.LastCheckpointID`, and a fully-condensed ENDED session is the most likely to have one.\\n\\nFiltering at the `findSessionsForWorktree` level would require either:\\n- A separate query method for amend (e.g., `findSessionsForAmend`)\\n- A parameter to control filtering\\n\\nNeither is worth the complexity. The current approach of filtering at the consumer site (PostCommit loop, filterSessionsWithNewContent) is the right level of abstraction.\\n\\n## 3. Concurrent session concerns (no lock)?\\n\\n**Not a concern in this architecture.** Each hook invocation (`PostCommit`, `PrepareCommitMsg`) runs as a short-lived subprocess spawned by git. There is no in-process concurrency -- a single invocation loads session state from disk, processes it, and writes it back. Two concurrent `git commit` invocations would be separate processes with separate reads, but git itself serializes commits via the index lock (`index.lock`), so concurrent PostCommit hooks cannot race.\\n\\nThe only theoretical race is between a running agent (which calls `SaveSessionState` during `SaveStep`) and a concurrent `git commit` (which reads + modifies + saves state in PostCommit). But the agent subprocess and the hook subprocess are separate processes with no shared memory. The file-level atomicity from the `.tmp` + `os.Rename` pattern in `StateStore.Save` (line 317) provides sufficient guarantees: each writer sees a consistent snapshot, and the last writer wins. The `FullyCondensed` flag is only set by PostCommit and only cleared by hooks that fire on session reactivation (TurnStart, SessionStart), which are temporally separated from the ENDED state.\\n\\n**No lock needed.**\\n\\n## 4. Is the condition `handler.condensed && state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded && len(state.FilesTouched) == 0` evaluated efficiently?\\n\\n**Yes.** All three checks are trivially cheap:\\n- `handler.condensed`: bool field read\\n- `state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded`: string comparison (constant-length \\\"ended\\\")\\n- `len(state.FilesTouched) == 0`: slice length check\\n\\nThe condition is also correctly ordered -- `handler.condensed` is the most likely to be false (only true when condensation actually ran), so short-circuit evaluation skips the other checks in the common case.\\n\\nOne minor observation: the skip check in `PostCommit` only checks `state.FullyCondensed` without also checking `state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded`:\\n\\n```go\\n// Line 783-786 in the diff:\\nif state.FullyCondensed {\\n    continue\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe original description in the PR says the check should be `state.FullyCondensed && state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded`. The actual diff only checks `state.FullyCondensed`. This is **correct as-is** because `FullyCondensed` can only be set when `state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded` (the setter at line 958 has this guard), and the flag is cleared on any phase transition away from ENDED (via `ActionClearEndedAt`). So `FullyCondensed == true` implies `Phase == PhaseEnded`. The simpler check is fine and marginally cheaper.\\n\\nHowever, the PR description and the code comment at line 783 say \\\"Skip fully-condensed ended sessions\\\" -- it would be worth either:\\n- Adding the redundant `&& state.Phase == session.PhaseEnded` check as a defensive invariant (documentation through code), or\\n- Adding a brief comment explaining why the phase check is omitted\\n\\nThis is a style preference, not a correctness issue.\\n\\n## 5. Hot-path concerns with the bool field (serialization overhead)?\\n\\n**Negligible.** The field uses `omitempty`, so it adds zero bytes to the JSON when false (the common case for active/idle sessions). When true, it adds `\\\"fully_condensed\\\":true` -- 22 bytes in a JSON document that is already several hundred bytes with arrays and nested objects. The `encoding/json` marshaler handles bools in constant time with no allocation.\\n\\nThe only serialization that happens on every PostCommit is `saveSessionState`, which already marshals the